Poland space.
Last week at the ministerial session of European Space Agency Poland was accepted by the twentieth member of European Space Agency as the second country from the countries of the former eastern block (after the Czech Republic, which it became full-fledged term EKA on September 12, 2008).
Poland began close collaboration with EKA in 1994 and for the subsequent years was accepted active participation in a number of the projects of agency.
But way to space Poland began much earlier.
Even before the Second World War Polish enthusiasts dealt with voyages into space, but this was not always encountered with the understanding.
I will resemble, for example, about A. Sternfeld's lecture, who on December 6, 1933 represented in the Warsaw astronomical observatory of idea from his innovative work “introduction into cosmonautics”.
The ideas of young engineer (1905 g. r.) left the audience of indifferent, Sternfeld recalled after several years, that only the doctor Ian Gadomskiy was interested in his work.
In 1934 in France Sternfeld won reward of Robert to Esnaupeltrie and Andre Louis Khirsha for “the introduction into cosmonautics”.
The doctor Ian Gadomskiy (1899 - 1966), whom was discussed above, more lately became the great propagandist of astronomy and cosmonautics.
It published in Polish periodicals hundreds of articles and wrote the row of the books, dedicated to these scientific disciplines.
Gadomskiy became the well-known world propagandist of cosmonautics, and his contribution was evaluated including by the fact that one of the craters on the far side of the moon was named in its honor.
In Poland was already in 1925 built the railroad trolley, equipped with rocket engine.
Unfortunately, the author of this idea remained unknown, just as to the detail of project.
It is not clear even, for the acceleration or for braking of cart had to be used the rocket.
Information about this trolley is known only from the press of that epoch.
Since 1933 Polish artillery began to think about the rocket arrows.
A study accomplished the section of the technology of weapon with the collaboration with professors Mechislav Volfke and Gustav Mokzhitsky.
It is evident from the preserved materials that studies reached the stage of service tests.
But works were interrupted with the arrival of German troops.
In 1937 in the specialized press the idea of the photoelectric of rocket-fighter, which proposed engineer Rogozinskiy, appeared, and in the following year published work “air rocket-torpedo and aviation rocket-bomb” author Lelivy-Kzhivoblotskogo.
Both projects were developed for the military use of rocket engines.
Before war itself with all designs of the military use of rocket engineering dealt the temporary scientific-consultative committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy), which coordinated entire work.
Committee was created in 1937, but after two years of its activity work ended because of the beginning of war.
The following scientific work, dedicated to cosmonautics, appeared in the Polish press after war, because of the work of the Polish society of astronautics (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
About the society are for the first time mentioned during by Noyabrsk number of 1954 of the journal “problems”, in which are published four volumetric articles on the astronautics.
In one of them the professor of M. sub-OTOHIV proposed to organize the society, which will be occupied by cosmonautics.
At that time the designs of satellites already collected revolutions, and it was clear that space studies - promising branch.
Since the beginning of 1956 the Polish society of astronautics (POA) attempted to enter the international federation of astronautics (based in 1951), and already in autumn POA became its full member.
But in the following year the first chairman of POA Kazimezh Zarankevich (1902 - 1959) became the deputy chairman of the international federation of astronautics.
On this post it remained to its quite death, which began in 1959.
Since 1956 POA made the significant contribution to development of very successful sounding rocket RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which became the first Polish rocket, which carried out scientific research.
The first type RM-1 was completed in 1957, while the first starting took place on October 10, 1958.
The rocket, capable of covering the distance of 1800 m, there were into the length of approximately 80 cm, and its weight comprised less than 5 kg.
Was subsequently built the improved version RM-1A, and in the summer of 1959 on the Bledovskom vacant land were carried out testing two-stage rocket RM-2.
This rocket was into the length of approximately 1,4 m, and its weight was about 11.5 kg.
The following version of rocket was able be occupied to already by this scientific work - rocket RM-34 could overcome 14.5 km, and observation of the wind at high altitudes was its task.
But in 1962 further development was stopped.
The successor of the first rockets of the type RM became rocket Meteor-1, developed in the period between 1962 and 1965.
Rocket was planned as its two-step, overall length it was 510 cm, and initial weight - 32.5 kg.
Were developed three types (designated as Meteor-1A, -1V and -1S), which were distinguished by the size of camera for the scientific equipment.
Rocket Meteor-1A had available space with a volume of 0.4 l, Meteor-1V - 0.34 l, and Meteor-1S - 0, 62l.
Maximum flying distance in all three types was 37 km.
In the period between 1965 and 1968 the development of rocket in the aviation institute passed Meteor-2, and its first flight tests began in October 1970.
Rocket Meteor-2 with a launching weight of 380 kg was capable of deriving payload with the weight of 10 kg on the height of approximately 60 km.
Then were built versions Meteor-2N and Meteor-3.
It is worthwhile to also mention about the entry of Poland in COSPAR (Committee on Space Research) in 1960 and creation of the national committee of COSPAR by two for years later.
Furthermore, within the framework of the program Interkosmos, Poland participated in the space research on the Soviet satellites, and in 1978 Polish pilot Miroslav Germashevskiy became the second interkosmonavtom after Vladimir Remek.
