This is not so, asserts Peter Tui, the professor of the Greek and Roman history of the Canadian university of Calgary, the author of the book “captivating history of boredom” (Boredom: A of Lively History, Yale University Press, 2011).
“In reality boredom can brag of very ancient history”, he says.
The Latin inscriptions about the boredom, dated by the first century, are discovered on the walls in the Pompeys.
In this case remains open a question about how we understand boredom.
Problem in that, speaks John d. Eastwood, the associate professor of university York in Ontario, Canada, that the understanding and vision of boredom frequently changed.
After studying the materials of experiments on this theme and after presenting the question to task force into 100 people, professor Eastwood and his colleagues arrived at the following definition: boredom - this when people “want, but they cannot be occupied by the fact that would bring to them the satisfaction”.
The difference between the boredom and apathy, he speaks, it consists in the fact that the being bored person does not make something, that he would want to make.
Nothing to make it is desirable with the apathy.
Basic in the survived boredom, he speaks, this “disturbance of attention and connected with this worsening in the mood and the sensation of the fact that the time is pulled slowly”.
According to the description the boredom can seem by very similar to depression.
However, professor Eastwood asserts that in spite of the possible connection between these states, the being bored people see the reasons for problems in surrounding peace and circumstances, and people, which survive depression, see problems in themselves.
It sometimes us seems that to us it is boring, when in reality to us it is simply difficult on by something to be concentrated.
In its study “the unoccupied reason: the determination of boredom from the point of view of attention”, published in September release of the periodical of Perspectives on of Psychological Science, professor Eastwood with the colleagues refer to the carried out earlier experiment, whose participants listened to the record of the voice, which reads periodical.
Some participants heard also the loud sounds of the not relating to the matter tv program, switched on in the adjacent room, others heard the same sounds on the low of loudness, so that hardly it was possible to dismantle them, but the third group listened to only the record of voice without the outside sound track.
Those participants, who heard television with the low level of loudness, they noted that it was boring, more frequent than others - it was difficult to be concentrated, but they did not know the reason for this and assigned this to boredom.
When we attempt to concentrate attention in the difficult or captivating task, the interruption of attention can cause boredom, speaks Mark J. of Fenske, associate professor of neurology at the university of Gvelfa, Ontario, and one of the authors of this investigation.
From the other side, when we make anything uninteresting, “for example, scrutinizing into the flow of articles on the conveyor in the search for marriage, the distracting music can help to avoid boredom”.
It is considered, it continues, that when people begin to rock on the chair or to sketch astrakmans on the sheet of paper, they make this from the boredom; however, now we know that in reality such actions simply help not to weaken physically.
“A study showed that the children, to which they do not forbid to fidget and to be twirled, learn better and memorize more information, than the children, whom they require to sit quietly”, asserts professor Fenske.
At some moments we all experience the boredom: with the delay of voyage (as in my case), listening to monotonic speech, examining uninteresting film.
However, different people demonstrate the different degree of tendency toward the boredom.
In the 1980's years for measuring such specific features the researchers developed the special “scale of tendency toward the boredom”.
